Your report indicates several usability issues.

By default, the C++ API may not flag errors as it used to. 
Since the change: 

        #if !defined(Z3_THROW)
        #if __cpp_exceptions || _CPPUNWIND
        #define Z3_THROW(x) throw x
        #else
        #define Z3_THROW(x) {}
        #endif
        #endif // !defined(Z3_THROW)

got in, it is likely that your application isn't detecting errors.
You should compile with _CPPUNWIND defined.
In this case, the following example will throw when adding timeout or rlimit to the optimization object:

     #include "z3++.h"

     using namespace z3;

     void main() {
        context ctx;
        optimize opt(ctx);
        params p(ctx);
        try {

            p.set("timeout", (unsigned)1ul);
            //        p.set("rlimit", (unsigned)2000);
            opt.set(p);
            opt.from_file("testfile.smt2");
            std::cout << opt.check() << "\n";
            std::cout << opt.statistics() << "\n";
        }
        catch (exception& e) {
           std::cout << e << "\n";
        }
     }

Optimization objects don't own "timeout" or "rlimit" attributes. They can be set on the context.
This is somewhat asymmetric to other objects, so I have added these two parameters to optimization objects.
With the change, the code will also throw an exception, except this time it will report that the check was cancelled.

I'm now halfway convinced that we could add this feature. I'm not yet convinced that we can implement it.

The easiest solution to allow implementing a `reset_all_param_values()` akin to the existing `get` and `set` functions would be to store the initializer as a parameter tag. This would make the implementation easy:
```python
def add_param(...):
    ...
    if isinstance(spec, lasagne.init.Initializer):
        param.tag.initializer = spec
        tags['resettable'] = True
    return param

def reset_all_param_values(...):
    params = get_all_params(...)
    for param in params:
        param.set_value(param.tag.initializer(param.get_value(borrow=True).shape), borrow=True)
```

The second easiest solution would be a second dictionary in `Layer`, called `Layer.param_inits` or so. This doesn't need to be an `OrderedDict`, we only need that for `Layer.params` so the parameters have a fixed ordering. It shouldn't be a `dict`, as deleting a parameter would keep it alive as part of `Layer.param_inits` then. Instead, it should be a `weakref.WeakKeyDictionary`. It would complicate the implementation a little:
```python
def add_param(...):
    ...
    if isinstance(spec, ...):
        self.param_inits[param] = spec

def reset_all_param_values(...):
    for layer in get_all_layers(...):
        for param in layer.get_params(...):
            if param in layer.param_inits:
                param.set_value(layer.param_inits(param.get_value(borrow=True).shape), borrow=True)
```

In either case, we need to investigate if and how this affects picklability of the models. Can they still be pickled and restored fine?

