@ToshiEAB
you can reference the code snippet below and also the rs-measure.cpp to achieve what you want.


    processing_block pb([&](rs2::frame f, const rs2::frame_source& source)
    {
     // source can be used to allocate new frames and send them out source.frame_ready(<frame_created>);
    });
    frame_queue q;
    pb.start(q); // Results from the block will be enqueued into q
    pb.invoke(input_frame); // Invoke the lambda above
    frame output_frame = q.wait_for_frame(); // Fetch the result, result will be from above "source.frame_ready" function.

From the rs-measure.cpp, you can refer to the block 188 for the whole picture how to use the processing_block:
**video_process_thread** thread creates **frame_processor** processing block, and the line "`frame_processor >> postprocessed_frames`" equals to "`frame_processor.start(postprocessed_frames)`". At the bottom part of the thread lambda function, the while loop keep retrieving the frame from pipe then feed into frame_process.invoke. The process then goes into the **processing_block segment(frame_processor lambda function)**, then you see the last line inside the segment "source.frame_ready(combined)" which will push the combined frame into the **postprocessed_frames** queue for other process to retrieve.

