Now the counters for the `accepted/received/sent` prefixes should be correct with this PR. The data in the example above is now included in another test

What is not working/supported are all tables other than `inet.0` or `inet6.0` in the master routing-instance. So in our example:
```
192.168.2.15          65002         54         49       0       1        9:01 Establ
  inet.0: 2/2/2/0
  bgp.l3vpn.0: 0/4/4/0
  inet6.0: 0/0/0/0
  vrf.inet.0: 0/3/3/0
  vrf2.inet.0: 0/1/1/0
```
The tables like `evpn` or `bgp.l3vpn` or `vrf/vrf2` are not supported. They were messing up with the `inet.0` and `inet6.0` counters which were not correct. To fix that in the code I had to pass the `instance` to the `_get_address_family()` function, so I could decide how to get the `address_family`

For the existing tests I only had to update the counters that were wrong, the rest of routing-instances are all still there!

