@mexon:
> I'm speculating, but maybe "normal" clients are able to reach the server fine because they're reading from whichever level of DNS cache, while Boulder is attempting to directly query the nameserver. If the nameserver randomly drops out for long periods, ordinary clients won't notice because they'll have N-hours-old cached values. Am I on the right track?

This is entirely possible. It's true that Boulder attempts to directly query each nameserver involved, and intermittent outages from DNSPod would result in failures from Boulder. Note that Boulder (and Unbound) do retry a few times, but on the order of seconds, not hours.

